		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.junowebdesign.com/?post_type=video&#038;p=5001</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Launched today Fixmytransport.com is a new website, which allows commuters to report any problems or complain about the standards of their public transport whether it’s by bus, rail, tube and even ferry services.This site encourages users to post problems so they can be delivered to the correct transport supplier and so other users can see [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Launched today <a href="http://www.fixmytransport.com/">Fixmytransport.com</a> is a new website, which allows commuters to report any problems or complain about the standards of their public transport whether it’s by bus, rail, tube and even ferry services.</p><p>This site encourages users to post problems so they can be delivered to the correct transport supplier and so other users can see which problems are posted online. Created by a lone designer over the past 18 months, Fixmytransport.com follows its older sibling <a href="http://www.mysociety.org/fixmystreet-for-local-council-websites/">fixmystreet.com</a>, which allows property owners to complain about elements on their street, or report any problems, which can be sent onto the local councils and fixed as soon as possible. Last year 60,000 problems were reported through fixmystreet.com such as broken street lamps and fly tipping.</p><p>Fixmytransport.com has been open for a limited time for testing, and due to someone’s comment about Woolwich Ferry’s Greenland Pier being in bad disrepair, it was renovated shortly afterwards.</p><p>These projects have had great support from local councils, MPs and for fixmytransport.com the transport for London have hopped on board.</p><p>This process uses crowd surfing where a sheet of contacts is filled in on Google. Customers can then report any problems on the site and they are there for all to see, it’s a bit like public shaming, but actually seems people are very proactive to get these particular problems sorted. This could improve services dramatically.</p><p>Other creations in this category as well as fixmystreet.com are sites like <a href="http://www.theyworkforyou.com/search/?s=department%3ATreasury+section%3Awrans+speaker%3A11036+speaker%3A20280+speaker%3A21830+speaker%3A16343+speaker%3A21290+speaker%3A21979+speaker%3A20281+speaker%3A15242+speaker%3A23731+speaker%3A13377+speaker%3A22053+speaker%3A20972+speaker%3A15269&amp;pop=1">theyworkforyou.com</a>, which approach local MPs and discover what they are actually doing for the local community.</p><p>So the next time your train is late, or a bus has been terminated, don’t sit around moaning about it, get yourself on fixmytransport.com make a complaint or report a problem, because you as well as hundreds of others will be helping improve our transport systems.</p>]]></content:encoded>
