		<pubDate>Wed, 10 Aug 2011 13:21:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Dave Wiltshire</dc:creator>
		
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.junowebdesign.com/?post_type=video&#038;p=4963</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The last 4 days have seen riots and destruction in London and other major cities in the UK. Unfortunately, it seems to continue, yet police are now taking a stronger approach, shipping in thousands of officers and using tactics such as water cannons to calm the riots.Social media has had an incredible role in the [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><strong> The last 4 days have seen riots and destruction in London and other major cities in the UK. Unfortunately, it seems to continue, yet police are now taking a stronger approach, shipping in thousands of officers and using tactics such as water cannons to calm the riots.</strong></p><p><em>Social media</em> has had an incredible role in the past few days, and this really shows what an incredible platform it really is.</p><p>Firstly, the dark side of social media was the use of platforms to spread unrest and messages of violence, so people could group together and cause chaos. Messages were posted on such sites as <a href="http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology/2011/08/10/uk-riots-facebook-invitations-see-2-due-in-court-and-three-new-arrests-115875-23333766/">Facebook and Twitter</a>, yet people quickly forgot these messages are public viewing, this has led to the arrest of numerous people and the fast track through the courts.</p><p>Because of the public nature of these social media platforms, rioters turned to using their blackberry messenger service. This service is not public facing and is encrypted but can be traced unless the user secures the messages to another using the exchange of PIN codes. Incredibly, research has shown that one third of Britain’s youths own a Blackberry due to the fact they are more affordable than android and smart phones.</p><p>Some messages were traced by police and national press, stating areas for groups to meet up, and again these have led to numbers of arrests.</p><p>The other side of social media is that amazing feeling of community and unity. Twitter trending rose including hash tags of #londonriots #riots and a site was set up to help communities clean up after the damaged was caused.</p><p>Thousands of people have tweeted and visited the page <a href="http://www.riotcleanup.co.uk/Riot_Clean_Up.php">Riotcleanup.co.uk</a>. A quick response to the damage caused by the riots and a great sense of community, helping restore areas.</p><p>The power of social media is incredible. People search for news, it’s in our nature to be curious, and want to know if such things are affecting people we know and our areas.</p><p>Think about what you can achieve when you harness the power of social media.</p><p><strong>Extra Video Content:</strong> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o5Qd0aNqDyg">BBC News on the power of social media during the riots</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://www.junowebdesign.com/the-power-of-social-media.html/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
